<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="161" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="161">
Genus 
<taxonomicName LSID="http://zoobank.org/B18334FD-AB44-421A-80FE-568854549087" authority="Falniowski" authorityName="Falniowski" authorityYear="2021" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Achaiohydrobia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Achaiohydrobia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">Achaiohydrobia Falniowski</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="0" pageNumber="161">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="161" type="type species">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Type species.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="161">
<taxonomicName authority="Falniowski, 2021" authorityName="Hofman &amp; Grego" authorityYear="2021" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Achaiohydrobia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Achaiohydrobia moreana" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="moreana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Achaiohydrobia moreana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by monophyly.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="161" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Shell broad, ovate-conic with a few flat whorls, rapidly growing and separated by a moderately deep suture; female reproductive organs with prominent, massive swelling of the spiral of the oviduct; oval bursa copulatrix with the duct longer than the bursa, receptaculum seminis prominent but smaller than the bursa, with the duct slightly distinguishable; penis tapering, widened at the base, without any outgrowths (nonglandular lobes) and without the distal papilla.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="161" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Derivatio nominis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="161">The genus name refers to Achaia, one of the ancient names of Greece and the Greek people.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="161" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="161">
The tapering penis with its broad base distinguishes 
<taxonomicName authority="Falniowski, 2021" authorityName="Falniowski" authorityYear="2021" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Achaiohydrobia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Achaiohydrobia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Achaiohydrobia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W. Hartmann" authorityYear="1821" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Hydrobia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hydrobia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Hydrobia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Paladilhe" authorityYear="1874" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Peringia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peringia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Peringia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The lack of any non-glandular outgrowths (lobes) distinguishes it from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W. Hartmann" authorityYear="1821" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Hydrobia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hydrobia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Hydrobia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Paladilhe" authorityYear="1874" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Peringia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peringia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Peringia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Radoman" authorityYear="1977" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Ventrosia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ventrosia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Ventrosia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The lack of the distal papilla on the penis distinguishes it from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wilke" authorityYear="2003" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Salenthydrobia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Salenthydrobia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Salenthydrobia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The massive swelling of the long spiral renal oviduct differentiates 
<taxonomicName authority="Falniowski, 2021" authorityName="Falniowski" authorityYear="2021" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Achaiohydrobia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Achaiohydrobia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Achaiohydrobia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from all other genera besides 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W. Hartmann" authorityYear="1821" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Hydrobia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hydrobia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Hydrobia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The molecular divergence between 
<taxonomicName authority="Falniowski, 2021" authorityName="Falniowski" authorityYear="2021" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Achaiohydrobia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Achaiohydrobia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Achaiohydrobia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the other genera (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">p</emphasis>
= 0.109-0.167 for mitochondrial COI) is typical of the genus-level in 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Hydrobiidae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
